non suae decuriae munere, lit. ‘ by the duty not of his own decury ’ or ‘ section,’ i.e. ‘ when the duty did not devolve on the panel to which he belonged.' For the exercise of their judicial functions the senators (who had enjoyed a monopoly of the iudicia from B.c. 81 to B.c. 70) seem to have been divided into as many decuries as there were quaestiones, and one decury may have been annually assigned to each quaestio. When from any reason a place or places on the bench became vacant, a subsortitio had to be made (from the decury proper to the quaestio) by the iudex quaestionis, on showing cause for so doing to the city praetor, and then it was open to any one interested to make objections.
